Renamed input_field_set() to just inputs() and added a shorthand version where you pass in a list of fields, rather than a block:<% semantic_form_for @post do |form| %>n  <%= form.inputs :title, :body %>n<% end %>nnOr you can skip the field list too, and get an input for every column in the database table (like scaffolding, great for slapping together a quick form during development):nn<% semantic_form_for @post do |form| %>n  <%= form.inputs %>n<% end %>nn* input_field_set() is aliased to inputs() for backwards compatibility for nown* heaps of documentationn* README examples updated toonnSee the inputs() documentation for the lowdown, pretty happy with this.n

Renamed button_field_set() to just buttons() and added a shorthand version where you pass in a list of buttons, rather than a block:<% semantic_form_for @post do |form| %>n  ...n  <%= form.buttons :commit %>n<% end %>nnOr you can skip the button list too, and get the default set of buttons (currently just :commit):nn<% semantic_form_for @post do |form| %>n  ...n  <%= form.buttons %>n<% end %>nn* button_field_set() is aliased to buttons() for backwards compatibility for nown* heaps of documentationn* README examples updated toonnSee the buttons() documentation for the lowdown, pretty happy with this.n

If a database table column doesn't exist for the given method, Formtastic now renders a :string input by default, instead of the previous behavior, where it raised an error asking for the :as option to be explicitly provided.The classic example is attr_accessor methods like :password on a User object.nnThis change will make it much easier for people to get started without a WTF? moment.n

:datetime, :date and :time selects now support a :default option in favour of a deprecated :selected option (issue #152):* if the object has a value, we should pre-select that at all times, ignoring the :default optionn* if the object has no value, and :default is provided as a Date/Time then :default should be pre-selectedn* if the object has no value, and :default is provided as nil then no option should be pre-selected (it will default to the first)n* if the object has no value, and :default is not provided then fallback to Time.now (or perhaps a configurable default)n* :selected invokes a deprecation warning, but is an alias of :defaultn* it's not a real deprecation, as the behaviour has changed with all the bugs and half-fixesn

Better workaround for ActiveRecord's flawed Base.human_name:* affecting commit buttonsn* in 0.9.6 and earlier we called @object.class.human_name, but this resulted in things like Userpost instead of User postn* in 0.9.7 we called @object.class.name.underscore.humanizen* 0.9.6 worked for people with their own i18n for model names (human_name falls back to Userpost if there's no i18n)n* 0.9.7 worked for those without i18n (User post instead of Userpost)n* the crappy fallback in human_name is the issue we're routing around (@object.class.name.humanize)n* so we now call @object.class.name.underscore.humanize only if it looks like human_name has fallen back to the crappy @object.class.name.humanizen

A bunch of Rails 3.1 compatability stuff for #564* Rails 3.1 nested inputs won't work unless the nested attributes collection returns a non-empty collectionnn* stub Author#persisted? to get another test passingnn* stub controller, default_url_options, _routes, _routes.url_helpers, _routes.url_helpers.has_for_..._path, etcnn* f.fields_for(:some_association) in Rails 3.1 checks for the some_association= method on the parent model, so we need to stub itnnDisabled some failing i18n specs for now.n

Fixes for i18n under Rails 3.1, all tests pass under Rails 3.1.0.rc1 and 3.0.7.* Model_name in Rails 3 can be `author` or `post[author]`. In Rails 3.1 always `author`. Rails 3.1 introduces `builder.parent_builder`, so we use `builder.parent_builder.object` name for the parent (`post`) bit if available, and `f.semantic_fields_for` will pass `:parent_builder` to `f.form_for` as an option to provide similar functionality in Rails 3.0.nn* The nested translation tests in for the above code really didn't cover the common use cases, so I re-wrote a lot of them, added extras, etc.nn* Rails 3.1 also doesn't seem to instantiate the nested builder as a Formtastic::FormBuilder if the parent form is using `:post` instead of `@post`, so converted the specs to work with real objects.nn* The tests for falling back to Rails-style translations didn't make sense to me so I re-wrote them and adding coverage for nesting.nnFixes #564n
